ormance metrics.\\n   - It mentions various evaluation tasks and datasets for different modalities (language, vision, speech) and discusses the challenges in smaller models and alternative architectures.\\n\\n2. **Implied Gaps**:\\n   - There is a need for new metrics and frameworks to better understand and compare the performance of foundation models beyond traditional evaluations.\\n   - The geometry of embedding spaces and its implications for model performance are not well-explored.\\n\\n3. **Brainstorming and Research Idea**:\\n   - The proposed research idea focuses on using random graph theory to analyze the embedding space geometry of foundation models.\\n   - This approach aims to provide deeper insights into model performance and differences that traditional metrics might miss.\\n\\n#### Formulating the New Research Idea\\n- **5Q Format**:\\n  1. **What is the problem?**\\n     - How can we better compare foundation models by understanding the geometry of their embedding spaces?\\n  \\n  2. **Why is it interesting and important?**\\n     - This research will provide a new perspective on model performance, potentially leading to more effective model design and evaluation.\\n     - It could advance the field by offering a deeper understanding of how models represent and process information.\\n  \\n  3. **Why is it hard?**\\n     - Analyzing embedding space geometry requires sophisticated mathematical tools and a deep understanding of both graph theory and machine learning.\\n     - Traditional metrics may not capture the nuances of embedding space geometry, making it challenging to interpret results.\\n  \\n  4. **Why hasn\'t it been solved before?**\\n     - Previous research has focused on traditional metrics, which may not fully capture the complexities of embedding spaces.\\n     - The integration of random graph theory with machine learning is a relatively new and unexplored area.\\n  \\n  5. **What are the key components of my approach and results?**\\