ession, latent position random graph models, and generative models.\n   - Incorporate your methodologies for variable screening, manifold learning, and graph embedding techniques.\n\n2. **Clarify Objectives:**\n   - Define clear, specific objectives that align with the refined research idea.\n   - Ensure the objectives are measurable and achievable.\n\n3. **Develop Methodology:**\n   - Detail the methodology, including the specific techniques and tools you will use.\n   - Ensure the methodology is grounded in rigorous theoretical justifications.\n\n4. **Identify Datasets and Metrics:**\n   - Choose appropriate datasets that align with your research focus.\n   - Define metrics to evaluate the performance of your proposed methods.\n\n5. **Expected Outcomes:**\n   - Clearly outline the expected outcomes and their implications.\n   - Discuss how the results will advance knowledge and lead to practical applications.\n\n### Refine the '5q' Format\n\nBased on the above steps, here is a refined version of the '5q' format:\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nFoundation models are becoming increasingly important in AI, but there is a need for more nuanced methods to compare these models, understand their scalability and efficiency trade-offs, and enhance their performance in specific applications. Leveraging advanced methodologies from statistical modeling, network analysis, and machine learning can provide deeper insights into these models.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we develop more nuanced methodologies to compare foundation models beyond traditional metrics, using advanced techniques from statistical modeling and network analysis?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nAddressing this problem will allow for a more comprehensive understanding of model performance, enabling better model selection and optimization. This will have significant implicati